{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657353","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657353"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:26:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:26:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19584"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19584","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19584"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.23,0.4,0.18,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12355"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116579"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"12355","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12355"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19584"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98572"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"29437"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29443"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116579","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116579"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe barium swallow X-ray shows a posterior outpouching at the level of the upper oesophageal sphincter (\u003Ca href=\u0022https://emedici.com/storage/media/73cc1186-3de5-4736-b36b-d9aeb3a2f5b2.jpg\u0022\u003EImage\u003C/a\u003E).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following muscles is primarily responsible for this abnormality?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Omohyoid muscle","Cricothyroid muscle","Cricopharyngeus muscle","Superior constrictor muscle","Middle constrictor muscle"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecricopharyngeus muscle\u003C/strong\u003E forms the upper oesophageal sphincter. During normal swallowing, this muscle relaxes to allow passage of food. Failure of relaxation can lead to increased pressure and formation of a posterior outpouching (Zenker\u0027s diverticulum) as seen in this barium swallow.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eomohyoid muscle\u003C/strong\u003E stabilises and depresses the hyoid bone but does not affect oesophageal function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecricothyroid muscle\u003C/strong\u003E tensions the vocal cords but has no role in swallowing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esuperior constrictor muscle\u003C/strong\u003E aids in pharyngeal peristalsis during swallowing but is not responsible for diverticulum formation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emiddle constrictor muscle\u003C/strong\u003E also aids in pharyngeal peristalsis but is not involved in this pathology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe cricopharyngeus normally maintains tonic contraction to prevent air entry into the oesophagus. Impaired relaxation during swallowing leads to increased pressure and eventual herniation of mucosa through the posterior wall, creating a Zenker\u0027s diverticulum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA Zenker\u0027s diverticulum is a false diverticulum (pseudodiverticulum) that involves only the mucosa and submucosa herniating through a weakness in the muscular wall. It typically occurs in the area of weakness between the cricopharyngeus muscle and the inferior pharyngeal constrictor muscle, known as Killian\u0027s triangle. The diverticulum progressively enlarges over time and can cause symptoms including dysphagia, regurgitation of undigested food, halitosis, and aspiration. The condition is more common in elderly patients and may require surgical intervention in symptomatic cases.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The cricopharyngeus muscle forms the upper oesophageal sphincter and must relax to allow passage of food during swallowing.","Failure of cricopharyngeus relaxation can lead to formation of a Zenker\u0027s diverticulum.","A Zenker\u0027s diverticulum appears as a posterior outpouching on barium swallow imaging."],"references":["Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98572"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19584"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21617"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21617","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21617"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/L4zphjEULAFzUj4xwG3XTFNICxqGf0.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/L4zphjEULAFzUj4xwG3XTFNICxqGf0.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":405,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98572","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98572"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-30T01:15:37+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-30T01:15:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12355"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116579"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"descriptio